{"id":"1902.04231","submitter":"Ricardo Vieira Soares","authors":"R. S. Vieira","title":"How to count the number of zeros that a polynomial has on the unit\n  circle?","comments":"Final version. Keywords: Self-inversive polynomials, Self-reciprocal\n  polynomials, Salem polynomials, Sturm theorem, M\\\"obius transformations,\n  Cayley transformations","journal-ref":"Journal of Computational and Applied Mathematics, Volume 384, 1\n  March 2021, 113169 (Available online 27 August 2020)","doi":"10.1016/j.cam.2020.113169","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CV math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The classical problem of counting the number of real zeros of a real\npolynomial was solved a long time ago by Sturm. The analogous problem of\ncounting the number of zeros that a polynomial has on the unit circle is,\nhowever, still an open problem. In this paper, we show that the second problem\ncan be reduced to the first one through the use of a suitable pair of M\\\"obius\ntransformations - often called Cayley transformations - that have the property\nof mapping the unit circle onto the real line and vice versa. Although the\nmethod applies to arbitrary complex polynomials, we discuss in detail several\nclasses of polynomials with symmetric zeros as, for instance, the cases of\nself-conjugate, self-adjoint, self-inversive, self-reciprocal and\nskew-reciprocal polynomials. Finally, an application of this method to Salem\npolynomials and to polynomials with small Mahler measure is also discussed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Feb 2019 04:03:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 14 Sep 2020 16:12:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-09-15"}
